title: Solana’s Annual Carbon Footprint Equals 18062 Flights From London to New York - CoinDesk
content: Pressure is growing for the crypto industry to take more accountability on blockchain-related emissions’ contributions to the climate crisis. The Bitcoin blockchain especially has come under wide criticism among environmental advocates for the amount of energy needed to mine the cryptocurrency, and the Ethereum blockchain’s transition to a proof-of-stake network was partly motivated by the desire for a more energy-efficient system.

title: FTX-Linked Project Serum Shilling Shitcoins on Twitter: Report - CryptoPotato
content:
According to on-chain sleuth Zachxbt, the official Twitter account of the Solana-based decentralized finance project Serum, which had over 200,000 followers, has been renamed ‘Luka.’

The original Serum account is speculated to have been sold to a different user since all the previous tweets have been deleted.

Sharing a screenshot of the account, ZachXBT revealed that its PFP avatar was replaced with Milady NFT and was used for promoting “shitcoins.”

For the uninitiated, Serum was founded in August 2020 by a consortium that included the Solana Foundation as well as the now-collapsed Sam Bankman-Fried’s FTX and trading desk Alameda Research.

Serum received funding from Multicoin Capital alongside FTX.com and FTX US.

It was once heralded as a core decentralized exchange platform and liquidity provider for Solana’s DeFi ecosystem.

The events leading up to FTX’s bankruptcy filing forced Solana DeFi projects like Raydium and Jupiter to cut off ties with Serum.

Several exchanges, such as Upbit and Binance, delisted Serum from their platforms. Soon after, the project’s native token – SRM – also lost over 98% of its value since its all-time high in September last year. It was assumed that the project ended.

Subsequently, a community-driven fork of Serum’s V3 program was launched and rebranded as ‘OpenBook,’ which has over 5k followers on its Twitter account.

title: Assistance League helps Solana Beach Head Start buy new school clothes - Encinitas Advocate
content:
Assistance League of Rancho San Dieguito (ALRSD) recently helped provide school clothing for 43 Head Start children. The shopping event, called Operation School Bell, was held at Marshalls March 21 and 23. Each child, accompanied by a parent, was allowed to go through the store to pick out school clothing and shoes. The clothing purchase was made possible by a $4,000 grant from the Solana Beach City Council, specifically for the Operation School Bell Program. ALRSD is grateful for the support in making this event a success.

Angela Fuentes at the recent Operation School Bell event.

(Suzie Perry)

It was heartwarming to see the children’s excitement and joy as they browsed the clothing racks, picking out items that fit their style and personality. It was clear that this event brought them a sense of happiness and empowerment. The parents, too, were grateful for the opportunity to provide their children with new clothing and shoes for the school year.

Floricelda Sanchez with her son Lucas Rosales at the recent Operation School Bell event.

(Suzie Perry)

ALRSD is an all-volunteer, nonprofit service organization dedicated to making a positive difference in the community. ALRSD raises funds through its Thrift Shop in Encinitas at 1542 Encinitas Blvd., along with fundraising events, individual and corporate donations, and community and government grants. All funds are used for needs in the community through philanthropic programs that serve children and adults. Membership is open to everyone. Find out more at ALRSD.org

title: It's official: 292-unit Solana apartments rising next to L Line's Duarte Station - Urbanize LA
content:
In a ribbon-cutting held last month, MBK Rental Living and officials with the City of Duarte marked the completion of Esperanza at Duarte Station - a 344-unit apartment complex located next to the Metro L Line. Now, the developer turns its attentions to a follow-up project on an adjoining property to the east.

Last week, MBK and R.D. Olson Construction announced the official start of work on Solana, the second phase of its new project on Fasana Road just east of Duarte Road. Plans call for the construction of a five-story building on a roughly 3.4-acre site, containing a total of 292 studio, one-, two-, three-, and four-bedroom apartments, wrapping around an eight-story parking garage.

TCA Architects is designing Solana, which is depicted in a rendering as a contemporary wood-frame structure. the building is intended to have appeal to a mix of tenant types, including students, families, and empty nesters. Besides housing, plans call for amenities such as a swimming pool, a fitness center, and a club room.

Outside of the building, the property will include an "entertainment alleyway" which can host food trucks and outdoor events. Pocket parks and a linear park with a dog area are also planned.

The project, which is being built by MBK in partnership with Haseko Corporation, is on pace to open in Summer 2024.

Solana and Esperanza also sit across the L Line tracks from the 110-acre City of Hope campus, which is poised to undergo an expansion that will increase its patient capacity by 1,000 and its employment base by 1,500 through the 2030s.

title: Jay Electronica Reveals SZA Has Him Blocked On Social Media - HipHopDX
content:
Jay Electronica has revealed that SZA has him blocked on social media.

The Roc Nation rapper made the revelation on his new “Khalas” collaboration with Swizz Beatz, from the producer’s Hip Hop 50: Vol. 2 EP which dropped on Friday (April 21).

AD AD LOADING...

On the track, Jay Electronica addresses the reception to his A Written Testimony album before expressing confusion as to why “Solana” (which is SZA’s real name) blocked him on socials.

“I did an album with Hov, lames let all their hate vent/ So I fell back three years like, ‘Go ahead, be great then’/ I popped out with Flygod, I popped out on ‘Donda’/ I popped out with Russ, then Vic Mensa and then Ambré/ I popped up at Spades and I popped up at Vandals/ And my sister keep asking why I got blocked by Solana,” he raps.

Listen to the song below:

While the pair have never had any public disputes in the past, Jay Electronica apparently asked SZA if she believed in God during a bizarre Twitter rant earlier this year.

He also posed the same question to Drake, Diddy and Questlove, among a slew of others, with the Bad Boy boss being the only one to respond.

AD AD LOADING...

“I believe in him beyond your comprehension,” Puff wrote back. “I give all glory to him. If my god ain’t in it, I don’t want it. LOVE.”

Jay Elec also took aim at astrology during the aforementioned rant, writing: “Motherfuckers will tell you mercury is in retrograde and don’t even have a telescope. Naw, I’m good. Salaam Alaikum.”

AD AD LOADING...

SZA has previously expressed a devout belief in astrology, and back in 2019 asked her astrologer Jaadee to publish her full chart on Twitter. However, it’s unclear if any of these issues were what caused SZA to block Jay Electronica on social media.

The elusive “Exhibit C” lyricist is just one of several high-profile names on Swizz Beatz’s new EP, which also features appearances from Nas, Lil Wayne, Jadakiss, Benny The Butcher, Lil Durk and A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie.

The six-track project comes courtesy of Mass Appeal’s Hip Hop 50: The Soundtrack series and follows DJ Premier’s similarly stacked Hip Hop 50: Vol. 1 EP which dropped last year.

In other Jay Electronica news, the the 46-year-old revealed in December that he’s working on a joint album with Curren$y.

AD AD LOADING...

Spitta was hosting an Instagram Live with fans when Jay Elec popped up in the comments section to remind his fellow New Orleans native that their joint project still needs to be completed.
